Dec 10 2007	They should be ashamed	Owner Hilton Corp. should be ashamed at how this historic property is maintained.The Waldorff Towers used to be a residential apartment, and it is now billed as the private, premier section of the Waldorff Astoria Hotel. It is supposed to have superlative service, and they charge a premium to stay here.I booked a room through AMEX for approx. $800/night, and was upgraded to a suite-- 33f-- through AMEX platinum. There is a private entrance for guests of the &quot;Towers&quot; on 50th Street, around the corner from the busy main entrance. While this is a good concept, they do not appear to have a doorman stationed full time at this entrance to greet those needing to drop luggage and leave their vehicle with the valet. So, I had to venture around the corner on my own to the main entrance to locate a doorman who could help me with my lugage and valet park the car. This is unaccepetable for a supposed first class hotel which touts the supposed personalized service on the Tower side.Next-- the suite. Substandard condition. Again, not what you would expect for a hotel in this price point. For example--1. Paint peeling in the ceiling of the shower, literally hanging down, ready to fall on one's head.2. Peeling and dirty wall paper throughout.3. The whole place felt shabby, tired and somewhat unclean, especially the bathrooms.4. Cheap plastic/vinyl roll up window shades.5. Floor lamp did not work properly-- had to be unplugged to shut off. And, one ceiling light in the suit had the opposite problem-- itcould not be turned off.The whole place felt somewhat drab and down-market.The thing is-- the place has so much potential. Good location. Famous name. Rooms are spacious with nice architectural details, and some nice early century furnishings which would be welcomed if the suite as a whole we better maintained. Evidently, Hilton is happy enough to trade on name and the former glory of the property and maximize its profits. Many better choices in NYC at this price point.	
Nov 24 2007 	Service fantastic - rooms a little tired	We spent 3 nights in a one bedroom suite in the Towers with our 3 year old daughter. We'd originally booked at the NY Hilton but got a last minute deal. Difference in service from the main hotel? They unloaded our bags at the taxi entrance and then waved us in the direction of the Astoria. When we said actually we were staying in the Towers, they escorted us to the front desk and opened all the doors on the way. I'd phoned from the cab to say we were coming and check in was instantaneous. Bags delivered within 10 mins along with a rollaway bed for my daughter. Suite 31T - We had a sitting room with flat screen TV, a bedroom with a very comfortable bed and a second TV, a dressing room and bathroom. Oh and a real 1920's wer bar room with cocktail glasses and an ice maker. The suite (apart from the TV and fax machine) was straight out of the 1920s. Decor everywhere was very much from that era and room was maybe a little dark - though everything was very clean and certainly no peeling wallpaper. Our friends were staying in 27R which was much brighter, though smaller. I think it was just the colour scheme that made the differnce though. We found all the staff - front desk, concierge, room service, housekeeping excellent - but I guess at that price you should expect that. The public areas of the hotel are fantastic - though everything is expensive! The mini bar especially so! We visited the executive lounge briefly - it's not very big, but I raided it daily to get supplies for my daugher. Fruit juice, fruit, croissants, yoghurts etc in the mornings and snacks in the evening. You could pick up takeaway coffee too. My friends got breakfast vouchers but they are diamond Hilton Honours card holders. I tried, but failed.....$25 for the american breakfast buffet! I think you can do much better going out for breakfast but we had it one day and there was plenty of choice, and other cheaper menu choices. All in all - the location is fantastic - walking distance to lots of shops and attractions. Service was fantastic. It was a great experience - I never thought I'd ever stay in such a hotel. It is pricey so not for people on a tight budget.	
