Oct 30 2007 	A Wonderful Stay at the Towers	We stayed at The Waldorf Towers from 10/24-10/28 to celebrate a 50th Anniversary and had a fantastic experience. We had a 2 room suite with a parlor, dining room table and kitchen on the 31st floor and the accomodations were perfect for 4 adults and 1 child. The main bedroom (which was very large) included a king sized bed, a large raised bathroom which included a separate tub and shower, two sinks and a separate vanity in the double closet area. The second bedroom had two double beds and a marble bathroom -- this bedrom was more consistent with other high end hotel rooms. It could also be closed off from the main suite. We used the Astoria Lounge on the 26th floor for breakfast everyday and afternoon hors'douvres -- it's a great place to start your day and grab a snack before you start your walk around the city. The Towers lobby is never crowded, compared to the main hotel lobby, which is always buzzing with activity.There are many comments about both the hotel and The Towers regarding the age of the hotel. Guess what? It is an old hotel, but doesn't everyone know that when they check-in? It is what it is -- a grand hotel with a rich history. It was my experience to communicate with the hotel staff prior to our arrival to ensure the occasion for our visit was one to be remembered and the staff went above and beyond the call of duty to make our stay memorable. From the doormen to the bell captain to the front desk attendants to the maids -- they all provide exemplary service. Treat them they way you would want to be treated (yes, tip them) and your stay will be great.We look forward to a return visit to The Waldorf Towers and another great experience.	
Oct 27 2007 	a classic institution	Booked a week at a junior suite two months early and then upgraded a week before travel to a one bed suite in the towers - paid about $950 for a $1400 room. So its not cheap, even at a discount - but the rooms were huge (maybe 2000ft total), the bathroom marble luxery, and the bed very comfy. In answer to a previous reviewer complaining that the fittings were 20 years old, of course they are - its a classic hotel from the 1930's, and for me that art deco history and aged furnishings is part of the point of going! Its also a central location, very elegant public rooms, perhaps slightly stuffy and old fashioned restaurants and room service etc. But thats what I would expect from a grand old dame like this, and its worth it for the experience if you like old world charm.	
