Sep 18 2007 	Much better than the normal rooms	After having stayed at the Waldorf many times, I think what you get is going to be potluck as far as rooms are concerned. My room in the towers was a roomy queen sized room with a standard hotel bathroom. The bathtub was larger than most bathtubs (though not a garden size tub) and the toiletries were Penhaligon's. I had a foyer that closed off from the bedroom which helped keep my room nice and quiet. My bed was conformtable and I even had a coffee maker in my room (which is not standard for normal Waldorf rooms). The room was decorated in a traditional way and much of the furniture looked antique. I enjoyed my towers stay much more than any of my other stays at the waldorf!	
Jul 31 2007 	Shabby but spacious	We have just finished 3 days in a Luxury Towers Suite at the Waldorf Towers. The first thing to note (because this is the first thing you'll see) is that the room was shabby. Really shabby. We are talking about six-inch wide pieces of wallpaper coming away from the walls, mysterious bulges behind plaster work, worn (as opposed to antique) furnishings, missing blocks in the parquet flooring, a very uncomfy bed etc. The bathroom fittings are at least 20 years old, and you don't even get 2 sinks yet alone 2 toilets as you would expect in a suite. The club lounge on the 26th floor is pathetic - literally three proper tables, with everyone else eating off a side table. I can imagine at peak times you'll struggle to get a cheap. No cooked breakfast options, and they have the nerve to charge for alcohol and close at 9pm!However .... there are a lot of postive things about the property. Our suite was huge (website gives range of 600-800 sq ft for Luxury Tower Suites and ours was certainly at the upper end of this). It had windows looking in 2 directions with, from the bed, a perfectly framed view of the Chrysler Building. The rate ($665 per night) was exceptionally reasonable for the size of the suite, which included a separate living area (2 flat screen TV's in all), a large dressing area (3 wardrobes in total) and a large hallway, plus the bedroom. You get to access all of the Waldorf-Astoria facilities which are impressive in scale and looks. And the location is central for most touristy things - walkable to Barneys / Bloomingdales and easy access to Grand Central for metros elsewhere.Its fair to say my other half (who really wanted to stay here, which is the only reason I booked it - I knew what to expect) was disappointed. However, by the 2nd night, we'd begun to overlook the shabby look and enjoy the huge amount of space and the general Waldorf environment. If its space you're after, this is very likely to be the best upscale deal in Manhattan. If you want an immediate 'wow' factor and modern furnishings, give it a miss and try Soho House, the Mandarin Oriental, the Four Seasons or, for a cheaper weekend away, the Ritz-Carlton Battery Park.	
